<dl id="n10084f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10084f">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10084f"> 84(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> only profiteers &mdash; / in sodawater biz</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">BUTCHER SUED. Mr. Kennedy, Loughrea, sought an instalment order against Mr. McQuaid, Loughrea, against whom he had a decree for rent. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Mr. McQuaid swore that he had to leave the house he was in, belonging to Mrs. Kennedy, and go to a smaller house in a backward place. His present contract with the County Home was to supply two sheep per week at 10d. per lb., and he was losing &pound;1 per week on it, but another butcher wa going halves with him.&mdash;Mr. Shiels: What was your army contract?&mdash;I supplied about 25s. or 30s. worth every week.&mdash;So you had an assured income of 25s. or 30s. each week?&mdash;I had only about 2s. or 3s. profit.&mdash;His honor: As far as I can see, the <mark>only people who make profit nowadays are those in the soda water business</mark>. Dr Comyn: Or the people in the S.P. racing business. <small> <a name="CT26apr24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CT26apr24"><cite title="source">Connacht Tribune</cite></a> (26 April 1924) 6/3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
